From our initial glimpse of the MxMH Survey Results, we saw that it contains 736 responses that span a wide range of information about individuals' music listening behavior and their self-assessed mental health status. Each response has background variables like age, primary streaming platform, and how many hours per day they listen to music. Participants were also requested to qualitatively rate how frequently they listen to 16 genres spanning from classical and jazz to EDM and metal on a scale ranging from "Never" to "Very Often." We also have quantitative depression, anxiety, insomnia, and OCD ratings on the 0–10 scale. The dataset further captures interesting individual traits, i.e., if a person is a musician or an exploratory listener. While most of the information is complete, there are some missing entries in columns like BPM, Age, and Music effects. Overall, the dataset is dense and valuable for the development of predictive models as well as the identification of listener profiles through clustering.

If we examine the summary statistics for the MxMH data, we had a wide age range among participants, from 10 to 89 years, with median age approximately 21. On average, individuals reported listening to music for about 3.5 hours a day, though it did fluctuate significantly—some listened for less than an hour, while others listened almost the entire day (up to 24 hours, which is suspect or background music). The 0 to 10 scores for mental health indicate anxiety and depression as the most common, with higher-than-average scores of over 4 for both. The median anxiety score was 6, indicating that the majority of users have regular anxiety. The insomnia and OCD scores were lower overall but also commonly experienced by users.

One thing we wonder about is the BPM (beats per minute) column—it looks like it has some exceedingly high numbers (e.g., 1 billion), and that makes it seem like individuals may have gotten those wrong or responded in inconsistent ways to that question. We will likely need to clean or drop that variable before we can utilize it in our analysis. Together, these numbers already indicate a good degree of variation in music behavior and mental health, and on this basis further research is promising.

2. Missing Data Analysis¶

In [5]:
# Checking number and percentage of missing values per column
missing_counts = df.isnull().sum()
missing_percent = (missing_counts / len(df)) * 100
missing_summary = pd.DataFrame({
    'Missing Values': missing_counts,
    'Percentage (%)': missing_percent.round(2)
})
display(missing_summary[missing_summary['Missing Values'] > 0].sort_values(by='Percentage (%)', ascending=False))

# Visualizing missingness using a bar chart
msno.bar(df, figsize=(16, 6), color="skyblue")
plt.title("Missing Values per Column")
plt.xticks(rotation=60, ha='right')

plt.show()
Missing Values Percentage (%)
BPM 107 14.54
Music effects 8 1.09
Instrumentalist 4 0.54
Foreign languages 4 0.54
While working 3 0.41
Age 1 0.14
Primary streaming service 1 0.14
Composer 1 0.14

In trying to find missing values for the MxMH data set, there are very well-structured columns with very negligible missing values. The only column outside the trend is BPM (beats per minute) missing in about 15% of the responses. That is a fact and reminds us of two things—first, whether the question would be comprehensible to participants, and second, whether input data is reliable because the previous summary statistics were already detecting anomalously high outliers in BPM.

These other variables with less than 1.1% missing values and in our opinion can be filled or replaced with the mode without causing any harm since they are nominal variables are few of the ones like Music effects, Instrumentalist, and Foreign languages. Likewise, During work, Age, and Primary streaming service with 1–3 missing observations respectively is not significant when handling data this large. We plan to fill these based on either the mode (for categorical) or median (for numerical like age).

As for the BPM column, considering its high missing rate and outliers, we’re currently leaning toward either dropping it entirely or treating it separately with robust imputation and outlier filtering, depending on how useful it proves to be during model evaluation.

In [6]:
# Heatmap of missingness correlation
msno.heatmap(df, figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title("Missing Data Correlation Heatmap")
plt.savefig('../plots/2. Missing_Data_Correlation_Heatmap.png')
plt.show()

To further examine if missing values are related to each other, we explored the correlation of columns' missing. Interestingly, we discovered that Composer and Instrumentalist were greatly correlated in their missing (0.6), which makes sense as those non-musician participants would have defaulted on both questions. We also see a moderate correlation (0.5) between Composer and Foreign languages, which might indicate a subset of more active or music users. BPM weakly predicts other variables, confirming our earlier suspicion that it was responded to differently. Generally, there is not high interdependence among missing fields, so we can each impute independently without needing a chained or conditional process. This confirms our earlier intention to impute sparse missing values and to think about dropping BPM due to quality problems.

3. Univariate Analysis¶

Music Listening Behavior¶

In [7]:
# Distribution of hours per day
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.histplot(df['Hours per day'], kde=True, bins=20, color='skyblue')
plt.title('Distribution of Hours of Music Listening Per Day')
plt.xlabel('Hours per Day')
plt.ylabel('Number of Participants')
plt.savefig('../plots/3. Distribution_of_Hours_of_Music_Listening_Per_Day.png')
plt.show()

From the analysis of music listening hours, it can be noted that most of the survey respondents listen to music for 1 to 4 hours daily, with a sharp peak in the 2-hour figure. The distribution is to the right, indicating that while most fall in the moderate listening group, there are some who listen for 10 or more hours per day — possibly from use of music at work, during sleep, or passive background listening. There are a couple of outliers somewhat surprisingly going as high as 24 hours, perhaps reflecting exaggerations or autoplay/streaming usage. This bias will be useful to remember later when analyzing what correlation listening time has with mental health scores.

Age of Participants¶

Our population demographics based on age provide information that the largest category of respondents is between the ages of 15 to 30 years, and their highest frequency is from 18 to 22 years. The curve of distribution is highly right-skewed, supporting evidence that people are far younger than responders in surveys conducted through other avenues such as Reddit and Discord, which draw mostly young viewers. Although we have fewer over 60s, we do have a reasonable spread to the 60s and even 80s, which may be of interest to contrast age-related differences in music behavior and mental health outcomes. This bias will be worthwhile to control for in modeling and interpreting.

Those outliers imply that some tiny minority of much older clients were included, but they're not in the main distribution. While these outliers are legitimate responses, we will keep in mind that they can influence range- or scale-sensitive models — so we may have to normalize or transform them subsequently.

Mental Health Scores¶

In [10]:
# Converting mental health columns to numeric
mh_scores = ['Anxiety', 'Depression', 'Insomnia', 'OCD']
for col in mh_scores:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')  # Forcing non-numeric to NaN

# Plotting histograms
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for i, col in enumerate(mh_scores, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i)
    sns.histplot(df[col].dropna(), bins=11, kde=True, color='mediumseagreen')
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col} Scores')
    plt.xlabel('Score (0–10)')
    plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('../plots/6. Mental_Health_Scores_Distribution.png')
plt.show()

Glancing at the four self-reported scores of mental health distributions, we can already observe some interesting trends among the participants. Anxiety is the most dominating issue, and a very high number of participants have reported scores between 6 and 8. Depression is also patterned but less distributed, with quite an even balance across low to high scores. On the other hand, Insomnia and OCD show a different picture — both are highly biased to the left, i.e., the majority of participants have low levels of these conditions. The majority of users have zero or nearly zero OCD scores, and insomnia is also predominantly between 0 and 3. This difference across mental health conditions is important because it will influence how we build classification thresholds, weight our models, and potentially cluster users in unsupervised analysis. The imbalance especially in OCD may necessitate techniques like class balancing or stratified sampling at later stages of modeling. These trends also provide the foundation for investigation of whether listening behavior or music preferences are associated with higher or lower scores.

Favorite Genre¶

In [11]:

From the genre breakdown, we can observe that Rock, Pop, and Metal take the top three most favored genres among the respondents. Rock particularly has a huge margin, having been selected by nearly 190 respondents, with Pop and Metal following closely with performances no less dazzling. Classical music also features quite high, perhaps because of its well-established association with relaxation or focus. On the other hand, genres like Latin, Gospel, and Lofi have the smallest following in this sample, and this can perhaps reflect the cultural makeup or listening habits of the survey respondents — who are predominantly youth-skewed. These tastes will be relevant when we talk about how genre choice can come to equal mental health outcomes and if there is some overrepresentation among high or low risk populations. It also provides great foundation for taste-based clusterization for listening in the absence of supervision.

The storyline quickly shows that by far the most utilized streaming platform is Spotify, which boasts over 450 users labeling it as their preferred service. This mass dominance also reflects Spotify's global user base, especially among the younger population, which aligns with our age groups in our data. YouTube Music and Apple Music offer some minor usage, and Pandora and other unspecified or customized streaming services offer considerably less utilization. This bias is one to keep in mind later on in our analysis — Spotify usage could be impacting genre variety or listening duration, so we'll need to control for it in some models or plots.

4. Bivariate & Multivariate Analysis¶

Listening Time vs. Mental Health Scores¶

In [13]:
# List of mental health columns
mental_health_scores = ['Anxiety', 'Depression', 'Insomnia', 'OCD']

# Setting up 2x2 plot grid
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 8))
axes = axes.flatten()

# Looping through each score and plot
for i, score in enumerate(mental_health_scores):
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Hours per day', y=score, alpha=0.6, ax=axes[i])
    sns.regplot(data=df, x='Hours per day', y=score, scatter=False, color='red', ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'Hours per Day vs {score} Score')
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Hours of Music Listening')
    axes[i].set_ylabel(f'{score} Score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('../plots/10. Hours_per_Day_vs_All_Mental_Health_Scores.png')
plt.show()

1. Listening Hours per Day vs Anxiety Score: We observe a weak positive trend, suggesting perhaps that increased listening hours of music are weakly associated with higher anxiety levels. But the data remain very dispersed, implying significant individual variation. This weak positive association is perhaps still beneficial in classification models looking for cumulative patterns in features. Including listening hours as a continuous predictor might have a marginally better effect on anxiety risk detection.

2. Time per Day vs Depression Score: Once more, there is a weak positive relationship between music listening time and depression scores. While not significant, the trendline does indicate that individuals listening for greater amounts of time may also have higher depression scores. That gives support to the idea that excessive music may mirror or even exacerbate depressive states — something with relevance for regression-driven forecasting models.

3. Time per Day vs Insomnia Score: In this one, the association is stronger than the others. When hours of listening to music increase, insomnia scores reported also increase. Perhaps it shows a behavior association where music is being used as a reaction to sleep disturbance. For model building, this stronger association makes "Hours per day" a key predictor for estimating insomnia severity.

4. Hours per Day vs OCD Score: The OCD plot has a weaker but still positive linear trend, indicating a slight increase in OCD patterns with more hours of listening. Although weak, it's trending similarly to the others and implies a general trend across mental health measurements. Even weaker than that, this might still be an influence on ensemble or feature-weighted methods.

Mental Health Scores by Favorite Genre¶

    plt.title(plot_titles[i-1])

1. Scores of Anxiety by Preferred Genre: Rock, Metal, and K-pop genres are revealed to contain higher median anxiety scores, whereas Classical, Gospel, and Latin are lower in medians. This could also mean that individuals who enjoy high-energy or intense music might also be more prone to anxiety, perhaps using music as a coping technique. Favorite genre is a straightforward discriminative feature that can be employed for modeling purposes to induce anxiety classification, especially when categorized or translated into risk levels.

2. Depression Scores by Most Favorite Genre: The pattern is the same in this case — Rap, Metal, and Hip hop are accompanied with slightly elevated depression scores, while Classical, Gospel, and Latin have lower patterns. It could either be due to the emotional content of lyrically composed material or the healing effect of some genres of music. From the prediction point of view, preference of genre can serve as a good surrogate for mood, especially if associated with listening frequency or hours/day.

3. Insomnia Scores by Favorite Genre: That's an intriguing plot: Lofi and Gospel genres are linked to the largest median insomnia scores, and it might be that those struggling to sleep are listening to relaxing or religious music late at night. Country, Rap, and Jazz listeners have lower scores. This is a clinically and clusteringly useful finding — we can cluster listeners according to their night-time listening and self-reported mental health.

4. OCD Scores by Most Loved Genre: For OCD, the variations are not as dramatic but nevertheless considerable. Lofi and Gospel lovers revisit their top scores, and so do Latin, Rock, and Classical lean lower. While there is high variance, genre preference does appear to encode for slight psychological traits, and can aid unsupervised clustering or add to supervised features if paired with other behavioral variables.

Correlation Matrix (Mental Health + Behavior Features)¶

In [15]:
# Defining genre frequency columns
genre_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('Frequency')]

# Defining mapping if not applied yet
frequency_map = {
    'Never': 0,
    'Rarely': 1,
    'Sometimes': 2,
    'Very Often': 3
}

# Ensure mapping applied
if df[genre_cols].dtypes.iloc[0] == 'object':
    for col in genre_cols:
        df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.strip().str.title().map(frequency_map)

# Selecting numeric features of interest
mh_features = ['Anxiety', 'Depression', 'Insomnia', 'OCD']
behavior_features = ['Age', 'Hours per day'] + genre_cols
selected_cols = mh_features + behavior_features

# Ensuring genre ratings are numeric
for col in genre_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# Correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
sns.heatmap(df[selected_cols].corr(), cmap='coolwarm', annot=True, fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix: Mental Health & Listening Behavior')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('../plots/12. Correlation_Matrix_Mental_Health_and_Listening_Behavior.png')
plt.show()

The correlation matrix shows depression and anxiety to be moderately correlated (0.52), as would also be predicted by the extensive literature on the comorbidity of these two mental health conditions. Other scores like insomnia and OCD likewise show small but significant positive correlations with anxiety and depression, suggesting that persons with one are somewhat more likely to report symptoms of the other ones as well.

Daily listening time is positively correlated with insomnia (0.23) weakly and with depression and OCD weakly positively. The trend from this is that people who listen to music more frequently may be using it to manage sleeping problems or emotional pain. Age is weakly negatively correlated with anxiety and listening time to music, so the younger the person, the more they will listen and possibly also feel more anxiety.

Genre frequency correlations show a low positive correlation between metal music and anxiety (0.17) and depression (0.20), with lofi music showing weak associations with insomnia and OCD. Pop, rock, and hip hop have weak but consistent correlations with mental health scores, implying genre taste can indicate fine psychological states.

There also are moderate intercorrelations among particular genres, i.e., pop with R&B (0.39) and rap with hip hop (0.32), which suggest clusters of comparable musical preferences. Such genre dependencies can be useful to unsupervised algorithms like clustering or dimension reduction to glean user activity patterns in the form of music taste.

The scatter plot shows a clear clustering of the young members, particularly between ages 15-30, having a higher likelihood of a high range of music listening hours, with most listening in excess of 5 hours daily. Variation in listening hours decreases with age, and the majority of the old members report less listening hours. The red regression line indicates a very weakly negative trend, which suggests that the music listening time tends to be lower with increasing age as a whole. While outliers exist along the entire range of ages, especially for young listeners, the trend indicates that younger individuals might be using music more thoroughly in daily activities, for instance, for education, mood regulation, or social activities. This can guide modeling by proposing that age may serve as a mediator between the impact of listening behavior on mental health outcomes.
